But once you do enable services on OS X,
the best thing to do is start

00:20:29.990 --> 00:20:34.600
enabling and configuring that
firewall for that protection.

00:20:34.640 --> 00:20:38.760
You always want to put up yet
another barrier to attack.

00:20:38.870 --> 00:20:42.700
Blocking those services and the
little image you're seeing there

00:20:42.700 --> 00:20:46.800
is the new application-based
firewall that's built in OS X.

00:20:46.830 --> 00:20:51.610
It was our ongoing effort to
simplify the complexities of

00:20:51.610 --> 00:20:53.540
firewall for the average user.

00:20:53.630 --> 00:20:58.270
I still am amazed at how many
times we're in conversations,

00:20:58.270 --> 00:21:01.820
even in very large organizations,
where there are so many

00:21:01.820 --> 00:21:06.300
challenges to folks understanding
complexities of firewalls.

00:21:06.320 --> 00:21:07.410
And that's just the case, right?

00:21:07.420 --> 00:21:08.620
It's so complex.

00:21:08.910 --> 00:21:13.420
But yet we're expecting
as IT folks for our users,

00:21:13.420 --> 00:21:15.960
our end users, to protect themselves

00:21:17.450 --> 00:21:21.070
It's either going to be done by policy,
by you all enforcement,

00:21:21.280 --> 00:21:25.270
but Apple takes the extra
effort to simplify the process

00:21:25.270 --> 00:21:27.700
for kind of the rest of us.

