Hi, I'm Kim Hersh from the
National Security Agency.

00:24:18.300 --> 00:24:22.050
And as Shawn said,
I'm going to talk to you a little today

00:24:22.050 --> 00:24:24.300
about thinking critically about security.

00:24:24.300 --> 00:24:32.240
What I want to do is just
give you a way to kind of

00:24:34.600 --> 00:24:46.000
[Transcript missing]

00:24:47.450 --> 00:24:56.470
Just get a good grip on thinking
about security and getting into,

00:24:57.340 --> 00:25:05.840
really into thinking about it and just a
step-by-step way of locking down systems.

00:25:05.840 --> 00:25:11.560
Most people want the step-by-step
way of locking down systems.

00:25:11.560 --> 00:25:14.990
They want it to be just kind of
a no-brainer way of doing it.

00:25:16.680 --> 00:25:19.010
the...

00:25:19.380 --> 00:25:22.520
When we develop the
configuration guidance,

00:25:22.520 --> 00:25:27.560
we design it to be kind of step-by-step
guidance to securing a system and

00:25:27.600 --> 00:25:32.320
it comes from the best knowledge
we have on the security features

00:25:32.320 --> 00:25:37.820
of a system and it's designed using
standard security design principles.

00:25:37.840 --> 00:25:43.970
And, but like I said,
most people want it to be a no-brainer,

00:25:44.100 --> 00:25:46.500
but does one size really fit all?

00:25:46.500 --> 00:25:48.940
Well, not really.

00:25:48.940 --> 00:25:52.880
There's too many varied environments,
differing requirements for a single

00:25:52.910 --> 00:25:56.140
guidance document to fit all needs.

00:25:56.140 --> 00:25:59.590
And trying to write several documents
to capture a majority of needs

00:25:59.800 --> 00:26:02.400
would still not satisfy everyone.

00:26:02.430 --> 00:26:05.760
So the approach we've taken is simply
to tell how to lock down everything

00:26:05.760 --> 00:26:10.340
as securely as possible and to give
some of the ramifications for not

00:26:10.340 --> 00:26:13.060
doing so where we possibly can.

00:26:13.060 --> 00:26:16.690
And this allows every organization
to use the guide to develop an

00:26:16.700 --> 00:26:22.160
individual security plan for locking
down their own systems according

00:26:22.160 --> 00:26:24.780
to their own particular needs.

00:26:24.950 --> 00:26:30.780
Okay, so using the guide means
knowing how to adapt them.

00:26:30.900 --> 00:26:35.920
Adapting them to fit organizational need,
organizational policy,

00:26:36.150 --> 00:26:40.550
sensitivity level of the data,
and balancing these needs

00:26:40.550 --> 00:26:45.060
and the easy use against the
security risk to the systems.

00:26:45.260 --> 00:26:47.390
All right,
so there are general principles

00:26:47.490 --> 00:26:51.540
that are followed when developing
security configuration guidance.

00:26:51.700 --> 00:26:54.440
These are the same principles that
should be followed when adapting that

00:26:54.440 --> 00:26:57.630
guidance for use in specific environment.

00:26:57.800 --> 00:27:00.900
Let's look at the security principles.

00:27:01.980 --> 00:27:04.660
We have separation of function.

00:27:04.790 --> 00:27:07.740
If at all possible,
you should have a separate

00:27:07.740 --> 00:27:10.890
firewall between the outside
networks and your internal network.

00:27:10.900 --> 00:27:14.630
I know a lot of times in a
mobile environment these days

00:27:14.630 --> 00:27:16.870
that's not always possible.

00:27:16.960 --> 00:27:20.770
Email and web servers,
those should be separate.

00:27:21.280 --> 00:27:26.630
Also, the user database should reside on
its own server whenever possible.

00:27:26.670 --> 00:27:34.150
Having all these services
reside separately means that if

00:27:34.150 --> 00:27:34.150
someone should compromise one

00:27:34.400 --> 00:27:42.100
has a strong authentication requirement,
and he's not necessarily going to

00:27:42.230 --> 00:27:45.800
compromise your entire network.

00:27:45.800 --> 00:27:49.460
Having good separation between
the services by putting them on

00:27:49.460 --> 00:27:49.460
separate servers and having strong
authentication required between the

00:27:49.460 --> 00:27:49.460
servers adds another layer of security.

00:27:51.290 --> 00:27:55.000
Never surf the web with
your admin account.

00:27:55.140 --> 00:27:58.700
This cannot ever be said enough.

00:27:58.780 --> 00:28:03.420
Use admin only for
administrative functions.

00:28:04.720 --> 00:28:08.440
Encryption provides yet
another layer of security.

00:28:08.560 --> 00:28:12.790
No remote login should be done
without some sort of encryption.

00:28:13.340 --> 00:28:17.590
Any services, especially network services
that are not absolutely needed,

00:28:17.910 --> 00:28:19.600
should be stopped on the system.

00:28:19.780 --> 00:28:24.200
This is true also of any
unused code in the system.

00:28:24.410 --> 00:28:29.130
One such case,
even though it's not a service, is IPv6.

00:28:29.130 --> 00:28:33.200
IPv6 is currently started automatically.

00:28:33.500 --> 00:28:40.420
Many organizations have currently not
yet switched over to IPv6 addresses,

00:28:40.420 --> 00:28:46.090
and so if you're not using it,
go ahead and turn it off.

00:28:48.130 --> 00:28:50.130
Kernel extensions.

00:28:50.260 --> 00:28:52.940
They can also provide
an attacker a window,

00:28:53.070 --> 00:28:56.550
so if there are any unused or
unneeded extensions in the system,

00:28:56.550 --> 00:28:58.430
they should be removed.

00:28:58.520 --> 00:29:02.210
Also, they can be a good place to remove
capabilities from the system,

00:29:02.380 --> 00:29:05.500
such as the ability to
use USB flash drives.

00:29:05.780 --> 00:29:10.880
You must be remembered, however,
that kernel-less extensions may be

00:29:10.880 --> 00:29:13.500
restored any time the system is updated.

00:29:13.500 --> 00:29:16.500
So, if any extensions are
removed from the system,

00:29:16.500 --> 00:29:22.690
they should be removed each time
an update is done to the system.

00:29:23.660 --> 00:29:26.470
Choose the most locked-down
configuration you can while

00:29:26.570 --> 00:29:36.580
still providing the functionality
that's required by your users.

00:29:37.880 --> 00:29:44.390
Always lock down anything
that is not absolutely needed.

00:29:44.880 --> 00:29:51.400
And last but not least,
you want to always give least privilege.

00:29:51.400 --> 00:29:57.800
This includes for the users,
for file systems, for groups,

00:29:57.800 --> 00:30:02.200
anything on the system, group ownership.

00:30:02.200 --> 00:30:06.450
You want to give the least privilege
needed for everything to work properly

00:30:06.830 --> 00:30:13.980
and for the user to be able to still
do what he needs to do on the system.

