00:39:31.600 --> 00:39:37.160
Best Practices for Browsing with
Safari Browsing the internet is where

00:39:37.160 --> 00:39:40.660
some of the greatest security risks lie.

00:39:40.660 --> 00:39:44.420
Some of the best ways to mitigate
security risks are in how you use the

00:39:44.420 --> 00:39:46.600
device when you're on the internet.

00:39:46.640 --> 00:39:52.200
Make sure that whenever a web page
requires a login that it uses SSL.

00:39:52.420 --> 00:39:57.500
or that it says HTTPS instead of HTTP.

00:39:57.790 --> 00:40:00.930
If it doesn't, don't log in.

00:40:01.190 --> 00:40:06.540
Also make sure that SSL is being used
whenever sensitive personal information,

00:40:06.540 --> 00:40:10.040
such as credit card numbers,
are being exchanged.

00:40:10.110 --> 00:40:15.270
There's going to be a small gray lock
at the end of the address to indicate

00:40:15.470 --> 00:40:18.100
that the connection is encrypted.

00:40:18.100 --> 00:40:23.100
Don't just click continue if the site
certificate is not properly validated.

00:40:23.100 --> 00:40:26.560
When a message comes up that
indicates the certificate is invalid,

00:40:26.560 --> 00:40:28.100
there's a reason for that.

00:40:28.100 --> 00:40:31.320
Make sure that any site with
which you are exchanging sensitive

00:40:31.410 --> 00:40:35.460
information has a valid cert.

00:40:35.850 --> 00:40:40.030
Make sure you log off and navigate
to a blank page when you are

00:40:40.030 --> 00:40:42.800
exiting a secure link in Safari.

00:40:42.860 --> 00:40:46.140
Don't just quit Safari without
logging off first.

00:40:46.140 --> 00:40:50.090
And always log off and quit
Safari between secure sessions.

00:40:52.890 --> 00:40:56.800
Okay, storing your sensitive information.

00:40:56.930 --> 00:41:01.050
Currently there is no way to
encrypt stored data on the iPhone.

00:41:01.050 --> 00:41:05.710
And though the iPhone is a very handy
way to keep a whole lot of information

00:41:05.790 --> 00:41:11.800
in one place to carry with you,
